{
  "format": "tiptap/v1",
  "doc": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "What Rank Controls"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The rank "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "r"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " determines the expressiveness of the LoRA adapter — how many independent directions in weight space it can modify. A rank-1 adapter can only shift every output by a scalar multiple of a single direction; a rank-16 adapter can independently adjust 16 orthogonal directions. Higher rank means more capacity, more trainable parameters, and more VRAM, but the quality benefit follows a logarithmic curve with strong diminishing returns past "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "r=16"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " for most tasks."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Formally, a LoRA adapter with rank "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "r"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " applied to a weight matrix "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "W ∈ ℝ^(d_out × d_in)"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " trains:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "\\text{Params}(r) = r \\cdot d_{\\text{in}} + r \\cdot d_{\\text{out}} = r(d_{\\text{in}} + d_{\\text{out}})"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "For a 7B-parameter model with "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "d_in = d_out = 4096"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " and adapting Q, K, V, O projections in all 32 layers, doubling the rank from 8 to 16 adds only ~16M more trainable parameters (0.2% of total), while potentially recovering meaningful quality on harder tasks."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Quality vs rank curves for simple and complex tasks (left), alpha vs effective LoRA/RSLoRA scaling (right), and recommended settings table (bottom)"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "What Alpha Controls"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Alpha ("
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "α"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ") is a fixed scalar multiplier on the adapter output. It does not change how many parameters are trained; it changes how strongly the adapter's updates are applied to the layer output. The effective forward pass is:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "h = W_0 x + \\underbrace{\\frac{\\alpha}{r}}_{{\\text{scale}}} B A x"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The ratio "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "italic"
              }
            ],
            "text": "α/r"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " acts as a multiplier on the learning rate specifically for the LoRA branch. Setting "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "α = r"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " gives scale = 1, leaving the adapter's contribution at the same magnitude as the learned weights. Setting "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "α = 2r"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " doubles it. In practice, alpha acts as a second learning rate knob that is cleaner to tune than the global optimizer LR because it only affects the LoRA path."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockquote",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "marks": [
                  {
                    "type": "bold"
                  }
                ],
                "text": "Rule of thumb:"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": " start with "
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "marks": [
                  {
                    "type": "code"
                  }
                ],
                "text": "alpha = r"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": " (scale = 1). If training is unstable or the adapter underperforms, try "
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "marks": [
                  {
                    "type": "code"
                  }
                ],
                "text": "alpha = 2r"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": " before increasing rank. If you use RSLoRA, set "
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "marks": [
                  {
                    "type": "code"
                  }
                ],
                "text": "alpha = r"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": " unconditionally."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "RSLoRA: Why α/r Breaks at High Rank"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "With the original "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "italic"
              }
            ],
            "text": "α/r"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " scaling, if you keep "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "α = r"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " (scale = 1), the effective update magnitude grows with rank because "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "BA"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " has Frobenius norm proportional to √r for random initialisation. This means the same learning rate produces increasingly noisy updates at higher ranks. RSLoRA (Rank-Stabilised LoRA) corrects this:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "\\text{scale}_{\\text{LoRA}} = \\frac{\\alpha}{r} \\quad \\text{vs} \\quad \\text{scale}_{\\text{RSLoRA}} = \\frac{\\alpha}{\\sqrt{r}}"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "With RSLoRA the update magnitude at initialisation is roughly constant across different rank values, so you can sweep "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "r"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " without retuning the learning rate. Use it via "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "use_rslora=True"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " in "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "LoraConfig"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Rank Search via Ablation"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Rather than guessing, run a short ablation over a candidate set of ranks. The following trains a model for a fixed budget at each rank and compares validation loss:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from dataclasses import dataclass\nfrom typing import Callable\nimport torch\nfrom transformers import AutoModelForCausalLM, AutoTokenizer, TrainingArguments\nfrom peft import LoraConfig, get_peft_model\nfrom trl import SFTTrainer\n\n\n@dataclass\nclass RankAblationResult:\n    rank: int\n    trainable_params: int\n    val_loss: float\n    val_perplexity: float\n\n\ndef run_rank_ablation(\n    base_model_id: str,\n    train_dataset,\n    eval_dataset,\n    rank_candidates: list[int] = (4, 8, 16, 32, 64),\n    alpha_multiplier: float = 1.0,   # alpha = rank * alpha_multiplier\n    max_steps: int = 200,            # short run for comparison\n    output_dir: str = \"/tmp/lora_ablation\",\n) -> list[RankAblationResult]:\n    \"\"\"Train at each rank for `max_steps`, compare eval loss.\"\"\"\n    results: list[RankAblationResult] = []\n\n    for r in rank_candidates:\n        alpha = int(r * alpha_multiplier)\n        print(f\"\\n─── Rank={r}, alpha={alpha} ───\")\n\n        model = AutoModelForCausalLM.from_pretrained(\n            base_model_id,\n            torch_dtype=torch.bfloat16,\n            device_map=\"auto\",\n        )\n        tokenizer = AutoTokenizer.from_pretrained(base_model_id)\n        tokenizer.pad_token = tokenizer.eos_token\n\n        lora_config = LoraConfig(\n            r=r,\n            lora_alpha=alpha,\n            target_modules=[\"q_proj\", \"k_proj\", \"v_proj\", \"o_proj\"],\n            lora_dropout=0.05,\n            bias=\"none\",\n            task_type=\"CAUSAL_LM\",\n            use_rslora=True,\n        )\n        model = get_peft_model(model, lora_config)\n        trainable = sum(p.numel() for p in model.parameters() if p.requires_grad)\n\n        training_args = TrainingArguments(\n            output_dir=f\"{output_dir}/rank_{r}\",\n            max_steps=max_steps,\n            per_device_train_batch_size=2,\n            gradient_accumulation_steps=4,\n            learning_rate=2e-4,\n            bf16=True,\n            evaluation_strategy=\"steps\",\n            eval_steps=max_steps,   # evaluate only at the end\n            save_strategy=\"no\",\n            logging_steps=50,\n            report_to=\"none\",\n        )\n\n        trainer = SFTTrainer(\n            model=model,\n            tokenizer=tokenizer,\n            train_dataset=train_dataset,\n            eval_dataset=eval_dataset,\n            args=training_args,\n            max_seq_length=1024,\n        )\n        trainer.train()\n        metrics = trainer.evaluate()\n\n        result = RankAblationResult(\n            rank=r,\n            trainable_params=trainable,\n            val_loss=metrics[\"eval_loss\"],\n            val_perplexity=torch.exp(torch.tensor(metrics[\"eval_loss\"])).item(),\n        )\n        results.append(result)\n        print(f\"  params={trainable:,}  val_loss={result.val_loss:.4f}  ppl={result.val_perplexity:.2f}\")\n\n        del model\n        torch.cuda.empty_cache()\n\n    return sorted(results, key=lambda x: x.val_loss)\n\n\ndef print_ablation_table(results: list[RankAblationResult]) -> None:\n    print(f\"\\n{'Rank':>6}  {'Params':>12}  {'Val Loss':>10}  {'Perplexity':>12}\")\n    print(\"-\" * 46)\n    for r in results:\n        print(f\"{r.rank:>6}  {r.trainable_params:>12,}  {r.val_loss:>10.4f}  {r.val_perplexity:>12.2f}\")"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Alpha and Learning Rate Interaction"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Alpha amplifies the LoRA update before it is added to the frozen weight output, which is equivalent to multiplying the effective learning rate of the LoRA branch by "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "italic"
              }
            ],
            "text": "α/r"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ". This creates a coupling between alpha and the optimizer LR:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "\\eta_{\\text{eff}} = \\eta \\cdot \\frac{\\alpha}{r}"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "where "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "η"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " is the global learning rate set in the optimizer. Doubling alpha has the same effect on the LoRA branch as doubling the learning rate. This means:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "If you increase rank but keep "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "code"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "alpha = r"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ", the effective LR stays the same — safe."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "If you increase rank but keep "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "code"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "alpha"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " fixed at a small constant, the effective LR shrinks — the adapter learns more slowly."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "With RSLoRA both issues are resolved: scale = "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "italic"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "α/√r"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " grows more slowly with rank, staying in a reasonable range."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import math\n\n\ndef effective_lr(optimizer_lr: float, rank: int, alpha: float, rslora: bool = False) -> float:\n    \"\"\"Compute the effective learning rate for the LoRA branch.\"\"\"\n    scale = alpha / (math.sqrt(rank) if rslora else rank)\n    return optimizer_lr * scale\n\n\ndef print_lr_table(\n    optimizer_lr: float = 2e-4,\n    ranks: list[int] = (4, 8, 16, 32, 64),\n    alpha_strategy: str = \"alpha_equals_r\",  # or \"alpha_fixed_16\"\n) -> None:\n    print(f\"\\nOptimizer LR = {optimizer_lr:.0e}  |  strategy = {alpha_strategy}\")\n    print(f\"{'Rank':>6}  {'Alpha':>8}  {'Scale (LoRA)':>14}  {'Scale (RS)':>12}  {'EffLR (LoRA)':>14}  {'EffLR (RS)':>12}\")\n    print(\"-\" * 72)\n    for r in ranks:\n        alpha = r if alpha_strategy == \"alpha_equals_r\" else 16\n        scale_lora = alpha / r\n        scale_rs   = alpha / math.sqrt(r)\n        eff_lora   = effective_lr(optimizer_lr, r, alpha, rslora=False)\n        eff_rs     = effective_lr(optimizer_lr, r, alpha, rslora=True)\n        print(\n            f\"{r:>6}  {alpha:>8}  {scale_lora:>14.3f}  {scale_rs:>12.3f}  \"\n            f\"{eff_lora:>14.2e}  {eff_rs:>12.2e}\"\n        )\n\n\nprint_lr_table(alpha_strategy=\"alpha_equals_r\")\nprint_lr_table(alpha_strategy=\"alpha_fixed_16\")"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "text"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Optimizer LR = 2e-04  |  strategy = alpha_equals_r\n  Rank     Alpha  Scale (LoRA)    Scale (RS)  EffLR (LoRA)    EffLR (RS)\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\n     4         4         1.000         2.000      2.00e-04      4.00e-04\n     8         8         1.000         2.828      2.00e-04      5.66e-04\n    16        16         1.000         4.000      2.00e-04      8.00e-04\n    32        32         1.000         5.657      2.00e-04      1.13e-03\n    64        64         1.000         8.000      2.00e-04      1.60e-03\n\nOptimizer LR = 2e-04  |  strategy = alpha_fixed_16\n  Rank     Alpha  Scale (LoRA)    Scale (RS)  EffLR (LoRA)    EffLR (RS)\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\n     4        16         4.000         8.000      8.00e-04      1.60e-03\n     8        16         2.000         5.657      4.00e-04      1.13e-03\n    16        16         1.000         4.000      2.00e-04      8.00e-04\n    32        16         0.500         2.828      1.00e-04      5.66e-04\n    64        16         0.250         2.000      5.00e-05      4.00e-04"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The table shows that fixing alpha at 16 while sweeping rank causes the effective LR to vary by 16× (LoRA) or 4× (RSLoRA), making comparisons meaningless unless you retune the optimizer LR each time. Always tie alpha to rank or use RSLoRA."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Practical Configuration"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A complete "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "LoraConfig"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " with sensible defaults and inline explanations:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from peft import LoraConfig, TaskType\n\n\ndef make_lora_config(\n    task: str = \"instruction\",   # \"style\", \"instruction\", \"domain\", \"dpo\"\n) -> LoraConfig:\n    presets = {\n        \"style\": dict(\n            r=4, lora_alpha=4,\n            target_modules=[\"q_proj\", \"v_proj\"],\n        ),\n        \"instruction\": dict(\n            r=16, lora_alpha=16,\n            target_modules=[\"q_proj\", \"k_proj\", \"v_proj\", \"o_proj\"],\n        ),\n        \"domain\": dict(\n            r=32, lora_alpha=32,\n            target_modules=[\"q_proj\", \"k_proj\", \"v_proj\", \"o_proj\",\n                            \"gate_proj\", \"up_proj\"],\n        ),\n        \"dpo\": dict(\n            r=64, lora_alpha=64,\n            target_modules=[\"q_proj\", \"k_proj\", \"v_proj\", \"o_proj\",\n                            \"gate_proj\", \"up_proj\", \"down_proj\"],\n        ),\n    }\n\n    cfg = presets[task]\n    return LoraConfig(\n        task_type=TaskType.CAUSAL_LM,\n        r=cfg[\"r\"],\n        lora_alpha=cfg[\"lora_alpha\"],   # alpha = r → scale = 1 (with RSLoRA: α/√r)\n        target_modules=cfg[\"target_modules\"],\n        lora_dropout=0.05,\n        bias=\"none\",        # adapting bias terms rarely helps\n        use_rslora=True,    # Rank-Stabilised scaling; safer for rank sweeps\n        init_lora_weights=\"gaussian\",  # alternative to Kaiming; both work\n    )\n\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    for task in [\"style\", \"instruction\", \"domain\", \"dpo\"]:\n        cfg = make_lora_config(task)\n        print(f\"{task:14s}  r={cfg.r:>2}  alpha={cfg.lora_alpha:>2}  modules={len(cfg.target_modules)}\")"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "text"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "style           r= 4  alpha= 4  modules=2\ninstruction     r=16  alpha=16  modules=4\ndomain          r=32  alpha=32  modules=6\ndpo             r=64  alpha=64  modules=7"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Singular Value Analysis to Validate Rank"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "After training, you can check whether the chosen rank was sufficient by computing the singular value decomposition of the learned "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "ΔW = BA"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ". If most singular values are near zero, the adapter has not used its full rank capacity — you could use a smaller rank without losing quality."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import torch\nfrom peft import PeftModel\nfrom transformers import AutoModelForCausalLM\n\n\ndef analyse_lora_rank_utilisation(\n    base_model_id: str,\n    adapter_path: str,\n    threshold: float = 0.01,  # singular values below this fraction of max are \"unused\"\n) -> dict:\n    \"\"\"Report effective rank utilisation for every LoRA layer.\"\"\"\n    base = AutoModelForCausalLM.from_pretrained(base_model_id, torch_dtype=torch.float32)\n    model = PeftModel.from_pretrained(base, adapter_path)\n\n    report = {}\n    for name, module in model.named_modules():\n        if not hasattr(module, \"lora_A\") or not hasattr(module, \"lora_B\"):\n            continue\n        # Compute ΔW = B·A for default adapter\n        A = module.lora_A[\"default\"].weight.detach().float()\n        B = module.lora_B[\"default\"].weight.detach().float()\n        delta_w = B @ A                      # (out_features, in_features)\n\n        # SVD of ΔW\n        U, S, Vh = torch.linalg.svd(delta_w, full_matrices=False)\n        sig_max = S[0].item()\n        effective_rank = (S > threshold * sig_max).sum().item()\n        report[name] = {\n            \"nominal_rank\": A.shape[0],\n            \"effective_rank\": effective_rank,\n            \"utilisation\": effective_rank / A.shape[0],\n            \"top5_singular_values\": S[:5].tolist(),\n        }\n\n    return report\n\n\ndef print_rank_report(report: dict) -> None:\n    print(f\"\\n{'Layer':<50} {'Rank':>6} {'Eff.r':>6} {'Util%':>7}\")\n    print(\"-\" * 72)\n    for name, info in report.items():\n        print(\n            f\"{name:<50} {info['nominal_rank']:>6} \"\n            f\"{info['effective_rank']:>6} {info['utilisation']*100:>6.1f}%\"\n        )"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Low utilisation across all layers (e.g., effective rank 3 out of 16 everywhere) is a reliable signal that the rank is too large — you are wasting VRAM and training time on directions the adapter never uses. High utilisation (effective rank close to nominal) means the task demanded the full capacity and you should try a higher rank."
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
}
